qas.question: Sweden's two high courts are what?

answers.text: the Supreme Court and the Supreme Administrative Court

qas.question: What is a type of case heard by the Supreme Administrative Court?

answers.text: cases concerning disputes between individuals and administrative organs

qas.question: How are judges placed on Sweden's high courts?
The ability to appeal a case provided by Sweden's court system is called what?
What is the Swedish term for government?
What other cases does the Supreme Court consider besides disputes between individuals and administrative organs?

plausible_answers.text: the Supreme Court and the Supreme Administrative Court

qas.question: What two courts are equally the highest courts of the land?
The Supreme Court appoints what position?

context: In Sweden, <a0_0><b7_0>the Supreme Court and the Supreme Administrative Court<b7_0/><a0_0/> respectively function as the highest courts of the land. The Supreme Administrative Court considers <a1_0>cases concerning disputes between individuals and administrative organs<a1_0/>, as well as <b6_0>disputes among administrative organs,<b6_0/> while the Supreme Court considers <a2_0>all other cases<a2_0/>. The <b8_0>judges<b8_0/> are <a3_0>appointed by the Government<a3_0/>. In most cases, the Supreme Courts will only grant leave to appeal a case (<a4_0><b5_0>prövningstillstånd<b5_0/><a4_0/>) if the case involves setting a precedent in the interpretation of the law. Exceptions are issues where the Supreme Court is the court of first instance. Such cases include an application for a retrial of a criminal case in the light of new evidence, and prosecutions made against an incumbent minister of the Government for severe neglect of duty. If a lower court has to try a case which involves a question where there is no settled interpretation of the law, it can also refer the question to the relevant Supreme Court for an answer.
